-- overworld.corelx
-- The first chunk of the NitroPackInDemo rebuilt in CoreLX: a walkable
-- pseudo-3D overworld. You stand on a matrix floor that turns and rushes
-- toward you as you move.
--
--   LEFT / RIGHT : turn smoothly (hold) across 64 heading steps
--   UP / DOWN    : walk forward / back along your facing
--
-- This is the acceptance-test-in-progress: everything here is real CoreLX,
-- compiled and run against the emulator by the test suite.

-- The floor is the real park image (a 1024x1024 source, matching the
-- walkable world's own 0-1023 range 1:1 with no stretch distortion),
-- imported to a 1024x1024 bitmap matrix plane (corelx_import park.png
-- ParkFloor 128 1 park_floor.cxasset). Any smaller plane size wraps/tiles
-- the texture well before the world's edges are reached, which is why an
-- earlier 256x256 import looked visibly repetitive from a few steps away
-- and put the building over a wrapped-around copy of the ground instead of
-- its "real" spot in the park. It lives in its own .cxasset file and is
-- DMA'd onto the plane by load_bitmap.
asset ParkFloor: image "park_floor.cxasset"

-- The building billboard: a vertical-projected-quad matrix plane (not a
-- floor) using the real building.png, imported at 64-tile size / palette
-- bank 2 (corelx_import building.png Building 64 2 building.cxasset),
-- matching the hand-built reference ROM's plane-1 setup.
asset Building: image "building.cxasset"

-- Interior floor and NPC billboard, imported the same way (interior_floor.png
-- 32-tile/palette bank 3, npc.png 64-tile/palette bank 4). Both procedurally
-- drawn placeholders, matching the hand-built reference ROM's own approach
-- (build_rom.go's buildInteriorFloorImage/buildNPCImage draw simple shapes
-- rather than shipping real art either).
asset InteriorFloor: image "interior_floor.cxasset"
asset NPC: image "npc.cxasset"

-- Tree tile, converted from Images/Trees.png (a hand-drawn 3x3 sheet of tree
-- variants) by a one-off script: crop one cell, downscale to 16x16 with
-- Lanczos resampling, threshold alpha<128 to background (index 0), split
-- the remaining pixels into two palette indices by luminance vs. the cell's
-- own mean brightness -- same 3-color (0/1/2) convention as the hand-drawn
-- hero/creature art. Staged conservatively: starting with just one design
-- (see the ROM code-size note on the hero sprite above -- each 16x16 tile
-- costs real, already-tight ROM budget); a second design can be added later
-- if the build has room.
asset TreeA: tiles16 hex
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 02 02 02 02 02 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 01 00 00
    00 00 00 00 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 01
    00 00 00 02 02 02 02 01 02 02 02 02 02 01 01 02
    00 00 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02 02
    00 00 02 02 02 01 02 02 02 02 02 01 01 01 01 01
    00 00 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01
    00 00 00 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01 01
    00 00 00 00 00 01 01 01 01 02 01 01 01 01 01 01
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 01 02 02 01 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 01 02 01 01 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 02 02 02 01 00 00 00 00
    00 00 00 00 00 00 00 02 01 01 02 01 01 01 00 00

-- Near-distance LOD for TreeA: a single native 32x32 sprite (a 4x4 grid
-- of 8x8 tiles, tile-grid addressed -- see spriteSizeTable/
-- spriteTileByteOffset in internal/ppu/scanline.go), nearest-neighbor 2x
-- upscaled from the same TreeA pixel data above (not redrawn) so the near
-- and far forms are the same silhouette, just chunkier up close -- a
-- deliberate, standard "size tier" swap (the same technique Wolfenstein/
-- Doom-era sprite billboards used), not a continuous zoom: OAM sprites
-- have no scale registers in this hardware. Originally 4 separate 16x16
-- tiles drawn as 4 OAM sprites (a software workaround); simplified to one
-- real SPR_SIZE_32X32() sprite once native hardware sizes shipped -- see
-- draw_object_sprite_lod below.
asset TreeA32: tileset hex
